collection_history
From the Rebecca Darlington Stoddard Collection.
condit

The broken handles have been repaired. The neck and mouth have been restored,
      incorrectly (so that the lip is rounded rather than overhanging and offset). Some chips from
      the base of each handle are missing, and the surface is worn.
context
Dernah (Cyrenaica)
date_for_sort
decoration_description

Herakles sits, in 3/4-view to the left, just left of center. He is nude, but reclines on his himation, beneath an apple tree that indicates the locus of the scene in the garden of the Hesperides (the daughters of Hesperos), to where he has come to fetch the apples of immortality, as his last labor. At left stands a draped Hesperid, profile to the right; a second Hesperid sits on a rock, in 3/4-view to the right, although she turns her head profile to the left, to look at Herakles. A third Hesperid stands in a near frontal pose, with her head turned profile to the left. She is completely draped and veiled, while the seated Hesperid wears a dotted garment that only covers her lower torso, legs, and left arm. A Pan (woodland god) perches on a rock at the far right, and also turns his head profile to the left, to face the hero. The snake, Ladon, is coiled in the tree, above Herakles, and a winged Eros hovers above the seated Hesperid.

Additional decoration includes an egg-and-dot frieze above and below the figural scene on both sides (the lower frieze encircles the entire vase); a thin egg-and-dot frieze above the main egg-and-dot frieze on side A; and palmettes at bottom of each handle.
